verdicts.fix_note:
The minimal correct fix is to write through the SAME array being iterated, not the mirror. Iterate `events` directly in descending order (drop the separate `anchored` copy) and use the loop variable as the write target, e.g.:

  events.forEach((event, idx) => {
    const cat = event.type;
    if (anchoredTypes.has(cat)) return;
    const contextTokens = generateTradeNarrative2(cat, context) || {};
    if (_rng() < 0.6) {
      const tmpl = HISTORICAL_EVENTS_DATA.find(e => e.type === typeMap[cat]); // typeMap lifted out
      if (tmpl) {                              // <-- only re-render when a REAL template was found
        const replacement = generateEventNarrative(tmpl, event.yearsAgo, contextTokens);
        replacement.type = cat;
        replacement.anchored = true;
        events[idx] = replacement;
      }
    }
    anchoredTypes.add(cat);
  });

Two essential corrections beyond "fix the index":
(1) Drop the `|| events[idx]` fallback entirely. Never pass an already-rendered event into generateEventNarrative — that is the root of the string-severity corruption. If no anchor template matches (occupation_infiltration / exile_return / demographic), simply leave the original event in place.
(2) Also rename the inner `const anchored` (line 892) — it shadows the outer `anchored` array; harmless after the rewrite above but confusing. Use a distinct name (e.g. `replacement`).
Optional hardening: guard generateEventNarrative line 520 with `pick(Array.isArray(eventTemplate.severity) ? eventTemplate.severity : ['major'])` so a stray string can never be indexed character-wise even if some other caller regresses.
Note: my probe also surfaced an UNRELATED crash (generateTradeNarrative2 throwing on undefined .toLowerCase when context fields are missing) which caused most probe runs to throw; it is not part of this defect and the confirmed bug rates are measured over the usable (non-throwing) runs.

The suggested fix direction is correct but needs two precise path corrections (both selectors are wrong on BOTH path and shape):

NEIGHBOURS — read the nested settlement and the canonical field, matching existing consumers (graph.js:261-267):
  const net = x.settlement?.neighbourNetwork || x.settlement?.neighborNetwork || x.settlement?.neighbourLinks || x.neighbourNetwork || [];
  return Array.isArray(net) && net.length > 0;
(Do NOT just point at x.neighbourLinks at any level — neighbourNetwork is the canonical write path; neighbourLinks is only a legacy alias that sample/fixture data carries.)

LOCKS — it is an OBJECT at save.campaignState.locks, so count keys, not array length:
  const locks = x.campaignState?.locks;
  return !!locks && Object.keys(locks).length > 0;
(setLock deletes keys when cleared, so a non-empty key set reliably means "has active locks". Array.isArray will never work here.)

Also note the doc comments are stale and reinforce the bug: line 42 says "non-empty `locks` array" and line 95 says "any save with neighbourLinks" — update both to the object/neighbourNetwork reality. Consider adding a unit test for computeReaderAudience + a hook-selector test using a realistic save (settlement.neighbourNetwork populated, campaignState.locks={...}); none exists today, which is why this shipped.

The suggested fix's general direction (read the real store keys) is correct, but the exact form in the report's note matters and must be: read from `mapState`, use `Object.keys(...).length` for placements (it is an object, not an array — `.length` on it is undefined), and `.length` for labels (array). Concretely:

  const m = useStore.getState().mapState || {};
  const placedCount = Object.keys(m.placements || {}).length;
  const labelCount = (m.labels || []).length;

This mirrors the already-correct mapDirtyKey logic at WorldMap.jsx:158 and the save toast at line 453. Do NOT use `(useStore.getState().mapState.placements || []).length` — that would also be undefined since placements is an object. (Optional polish, matching the autosave dirty-key, would also count markers/forests, but the report scopes the fix to placements+labels, which is sufficient to restore the P112/M-7 warning.)
